**Abstract:**
Major essay titled "For chapter 1 on Searle" containing extended quotations from Searle's Speech Acts and detailed critical commentary. Develops distinction between speculative understanding (Searle) and practical understanding (Monasterio). Argues Searle's separation of illocutionary from perlocutionary effects is mistaken because he analyzes language as read or observed, not as actually used in interactive commerce. Develops Helen Keller example.

**AI Recommendation:** Draft book chapter on Searle; relates to 98-APR and 98-NOV series.

